I am checking the status for every second and status is reported as 'created' for 30sec, even though docker cli says container is running.

the below workaround works, here I am getting new container object every time

```python
def launch_and_check(self):
        if self.cnt_enc.status != 'running':
            self.cnt_enc.start()

            wait_cnt = 30
            while (self.cnt_enc.status != 'running') & (wait_cnt != 0):
                print(self.cnt_enc.status)
                # update container object
                self.cnt_enc = self.dck_clnt.containers.get(CNT_SWK_ENC)
                time.sleep(1)
                wait_cnt = wait_cnt - 1

            if wait_cnt == 0:
                raise Exception('Unable to start '+CNT_SWK_ENC)
        else:
            print('running already')
```

fontmake currently has a “preprocess” function to handle glyph names with hyphens. (In Glyphs files, glyphs can contain hyphens in their names, but hyphens are not valid in Adobe feature files).

However, the current implementation is **extremely** fragile: It tries to extract glyph names from the glyphs source, under the (wrong) assumption that anything with a `name` property in the Glyphs source is probably a glyph. Then, it just runs a string replace on the entire input, in the (wrong) hope that those rewrites won’t affect anything else but the glyph name.

An example where this doesn’t work is https://github.com/googlei18n/fontmake/issues/247. Here, the font contained the following (abbreviated) dictionary with TrueType hinting zones. fontmake wrongly recognizes the string “B: -219” as a glyph name, rewrites it to “B: .219”, and then it shoves it into glyphsLib.

```p
{
name = TTFZones;
value = (
{
name = "B: 0";
position = 0;
size = -15;
},
{
name = "B: -219";
position = -219;
size = -18;
}
);
```

Instead of doing such hackery, I think fontmake should pass the original, unmodified glyphs file to glyphsLib. It’s the task of glyphsLib to deal with valid input Glyphs files, and convert this to valid UFO with valid OpenType feature files. Therefore, it’s clearly within the scope of glyphsLib to know what constitutes a valid glyph name in what file format. Of course it’s necessary to handle this unfortunate mismatch, but for doing this correctly, one needs to parse the file. So the place for doing such rewrites should be glyphsLib and not fontmake.

[This notebook](http://nbviewer.ipython.org/urls/dl.dropbox.com/s/5cfyj0b046wq3ny/Making%20Bandpass%20Faster.ipynb?dl=0) benchmarks several different implementations of `bandpass`. I arrived at one that is twice as fast as trackpy's current implementation and up to 4X as fast with reasonable compromises in accuracy.

@nkeim, @caspervdw, @tacaswell and anyone else who is interested, would you run this notebook locally and confirm my timings? If this is correct and reproducible, I will make a PR to replace the current bandpass.

Unfortunately, the winning implementation does not allow us to hook into FFTW. Taking the long view, I don't want to completely blow away our work with FFTW even if it turns out to be slower. Instead, we can maintain several functions that give identical results, making `preprocessing.py` into a (very boring) research experiment on bandpass implementations in Python. The fastest one will be used by `locate(..., preprocess=True)`, but the others will be maintained for tinkering or future improvement.

