I use a D435 realsense camera.

on sdk 2.15, we can apply colormap on depth camera this way: 
```cpp
rs2::colorizer color_map;
rs2::frame depth;
depth = colormap(data.get_depth_frame());
```
It don't seem to work any more on 2.16 I got this error : 
```
/home/user/Documents/test_realsense/src/rs-capture.cpp:113:49: error: no match for call to ‘(rs2::colorizer) (rs2::depth_frame)’
         depth = color_map(data.get_depth_frame());
```

This methode from sdk test case still work:
```cpp
rs2::colorizer color_map;
rs2::frame depth;
depth = data.get_depth_frame().apply_filter(color_map);
```

This change was not mentioned in changelog so it's maybe a bug : https://communities.intel.com/thread/128477

| Required Info                         |                       |
|---------------------------------|----------------|
| Camera Model                       | D435              |
| Firmware Version                   | 05.09.13.00    |
| Operating System & Version |   Win 10         |
| Platform                                 | PC                  |
| SDK Version                           |  2.13.0            |
| Language                               |  C++              | 
| Segment			         |  Biometrics    | 

### Issue Description

On a 8 core box, the following code seems to be using 100% CPU across all the cores.

```cpp
int main(int argc, char * argv[]) try
{
    // Declare depth colorizer for pretty visualization of depth data
    rs2::colorizer color_map;

    //Create a configuration for configuring the pipeline with a non default profile
    rs2::config cfg;

    //Add desired streams to configuration
    cfg.enable_stream(RS2_STREAM_COLOR, 1920, 1080, RS2_FORMAT_BGR8, 30);

    // Declare RealSense pipeline, encapsulating the actual device and sensors
    rs2::pipeline pipe;
    // Start streaming with default recommended configuration
    pipe.start(cfg);

    while (waitKey(10))
    {
        auto frameset = pipe.wait_for_frames(); // Wait for next set of frames from the camera
        auto frame = color_map(frameset.get_color_frame());

        // Query frame size (width and height)
        const int w = frame.as<rs2::video_frame>().get_width();
        const int h = frame.as<rs2::video_frame>().get_height();
    }

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

Apparently this is caused by

```cpp
    rs2::pipeline pipe;
    // Start streaming with default recommended configuration
    pipe.start();
```

When `pipe.start()` is commented out, the CPU usage falls below 20% (even that's high, but we can come to that at a later stage).

If you define the following two types, or types that follow this pattern (Same model, different names). The relay node resolver resolves the incorrect name (and therefore incorrect globalID) for the type registered 2nd. 

```python
class ThingA(DjangoObjectType):
    class Meta:
        model = Thing
        name = 'ThingA'
        interfaces = (relay.Node, )

class ThingB(DjangoObjectType):
    class Meta:
        model = Thing
        name = 'ThingB'
        interfaces = (relay.Node, )
```
Query (ThingA globalID) : 
```
{
  node(id: "GhpbmdBOjE=") {
    id // "GhpbmdBOjE=" Correct!
  }
}
```
Query (ThingB globalID)
```
{
  node(id: "VGhpbmdCOjE=") {
    id // "GhpbmdBOjE=" Incorrect :(
  }
}
```

It appears that [there is some commented out code to warn about this.](https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene-django/blob/master/graphene_django/registry.py#L13-L15) However, it is commented out so I am unsure what the intention of the author was.

I am really just looking to see if this is "as designed". @syrusakbary

